<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:center;"><font color=3D"#33CCF=
F" size=3D"4"><strong>What is the problem with using the key a =3D 4 and b =
=3D 5?</strong></font></div>

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;">This key creates the=
 situation where more than one plaintext letter is encrypted to the same ci=
phertext letter (for example, above both "e" and "r" encipher to "V"). This=
 means that when it comes to decrypting, the recipient will be unable to kn=
ow which one of the plaintext letters has been used. Clearly this is a huge=
 problem in using the Affine Cipher, and it is essential for the key to be =
chosen carefully.</div>

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:center;"><font color=3D"#33CCF=
F" size=3D"4"><strong>Can you find other keys that have the same problem?<b=
r></strong></font></div>

